==Offseason== *July 7:Bianca Smith played basketball with a group from USA Athletes International, an organization that gives amateur athletes the opportunity to participate on an international stage. Smith teamed up with the three former Central Michigan University Chippewas â Sharonda Hurd, Latisha Luckett and Angel Chan as well as Prairie View A&Mâs Gaati Werema, IPFWâs Jordan Zuppe, Cornellâs Lauren Benson, Breynna Winkler of Gardner-Webb and Vanderbiltâs Jence Rhoads. In all, three different teams â two womenâs, one men â were part of the USAAI travel party.
Six of the seven games were played in Vienna at the Pentecost Tournament. The team played two games a day, competing against teams from all over Europe. After the three-day tournament, USAAI took a six hour trip into the Czech Republic for a game there.<ref>http://www.cubuffs.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=3910&SPID=258&DB_OEM_ID=600&ATCLID=3761599</ref>
*July 21: University of Colorado sophomore forward Julie Seabrook will be playing for the Canada National Junior Team at the 2009 FIBA U19 World Championship for Women, to be contested July 23-August 2 in Bangkok, Thailand.<ref>http://www.cubuffs.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=3910&SPID=258&DB_OEM_ID=600&ATCLID=3748551</ref>
===Freshmen=== *April 16: Kailah Bailey has signed a National Letter of Intent to play basketball at the University of Colorado in 2009-10. Bailey is a 6-0 power forward from Omaha, Neb., was listed as the 9th best available unsigned player for 2009 according to the Collegiate Girls Basketball Report.<ref>http://www.cubuffs.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=3910&SPID=258&DB_OEM_ID=600&ATCLID=3721228</ref> Bailey is the fifth player in CUâs Class of 2009, joining Janeesa âChuckyâ Jeffery, a 5-10 guard from Colorado Springs (Sierra High School), Brenna Malcolm-Peck, a 6-2 forward from Boulder (Horizon), Meagan Malcolm-Peck, a 6-2 forward from Boulder (Horizon) and Melissa MacFarlane, a 6-7 center from Omaha (Millard North). The 2009 class includes three Colorado signees. This is the largest contingent from the state to come to CU since 1997.
